english:
  title: Preface to the New Eastern Literature Selection
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The achievements rise so high they defy naming. The governance and teachings have already flourished beyond the ancients, and the literary arts shine forth worthy of record. Yet their creation awaited this enlightened age. Thus we have compiled this new collection, humbly offering it to Your Majesty's perusal.

    I reflect that since knotted cords transformed into written characters, our Way has dwelt within words. The sublime and wondrous essence of the Records of Shun and Counsels of Yu truly transmit the very heart-method of a hundred kings. The grand and boundless pronouncements of the Zhou Declarations and the Shang Vessels embody the timely governance and teaching of three dynasties. These Six Classics of the ancient sages run parallel with the cosmic breath and its four seasons in eternal circulation.

    Yet the times themselves know rise and fall, and the literary arts display heights and depths. The ten chapters of Zhuangzi shift and turn with strange magnificence, while the chronicles of Zuo are awash in extravagant excess. Fortunately, the thread of culture has not been wholly lost—we may yet trace its fragments. Through Han and Tang, through Tang and Song, the hundred schools flourished. As wind became the Li Sao and the Li Sao became poetry, all forms arose together. Though their phrases differ in refinement and roughness, all ultimately return to the movements of human nature. For works to endure in transmission, they must be gathered and refined. When the Prince of Zhao Ming compiled the Selections, the ancient prose remained preserved. When Zhen Dexiu gathered the Literary Essence, the orthodox transmission alone survived. With such accomplishments in each age, people could survey the whole of our heritage.

    Our eastern land, at the sea's rim, has long been called a nation of culture and letters. When the Viscount of Ji expounded the Nine Categories, our eastern people first received this blessing. When Silla scholars entered the Tang academy, none in the north preceded them. The literary wind grew mighty in Goryeo, and virtue and teaching reached their zenith in this enlightened age. Here and there arose men renowned in their generation, all born in their proper time. Looking upward to the sage-kings, downward to the scholars of Lu and Zou, they championed the Six Classics, followed Ban and Ma, surpassed Qu and Song, and mastered all the literary schools. Search through thousands upon thousands of years—the skilled in letters are not merely one or two. Though their sounds differ, high and low, each in poetry and prose pursued excellence, giving fullest voice to their gifts. This is what we call things singing their nature well. Who would not say that literature dwells here?

    Yet surviving manuscripts are precious few, and what has been collected remains scanty. The National Mirror compiled by Gim Tae-hyeon grows thin and superficial; the Eastern Literature authored by Choe Hae suffers from grave omissions. This weighs upon our hearts as scholars, and surely marks a gap in the cultural heritage. We have carefully considered how Your Majesty embodies the perfect unity of Shun, continues the cultural vision of Yao, and perceives how refined taste and governance flow together. Understanding that literature is the vessel carrying the Way, you have gathered the essence of past sages to serve as models for future learners. We humble servants have received your command and have sought out manuscripts everywhere. Though we lack the keen eye that judges horses, unable to distinguish bay from black, and though our hearts yearn to measure the ocean, we cannot always part the pure from the murky. We have simply exhausted our effort and made rough distinctions. Should our organization accord with proper form, and our gathering leave out neither precious nor humble things, then perhaps we have avoided discarding pearls in sifting the sand—though we dare not claim to have found gold in the grains of dust. Altogether spanning many centuries and hundreds of authors, we have obtained poetry and prose filling some ten volumes. We humbly present these for Your Majesty's leisure perusal. Though our selections lack refinement and may not fully realize the authors' intentions, does it not follow that one who loves antiquity with keen attention brings no shame to the act of compilation itself?
  footnotes:
    - 'The Six Classics (육경): the foundational texts of Confucian learning including the Book of Changes, Book of History, Book of Poetry, Book of Rites, Spring and Autumn Annals, and Records of Music.'
    - 'Zhuangzi''s ten chapters (남화십편): referring to the philosophical work of Zhuangzi and its many imaginative transformations and profound ideas.'
    - 'Prince of Zhao Ming''s Selections (소명태자): the famous Wenxuan (文選), an important anthology of Chinese literature compiled in the 6th century.'
    - 'Ban and Ma (반마): Ban Gu and Sima Qian, celebrated historians and literary masters of ancient China.'
    - 'Qu and Song (굴송): Qu Yuan and Song Yu, celebrated poets of the Warring States period known for their elegance and innovation.'
